<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=3343&amp;p=23883#p23883"><![CDATA[
I'm no ee expert, but you should do some reading up on how to create a circuit with LEDs in it.  Since the resistance in an LED is so low, it's usually necessary to connect it in series with a resistor.<br /><br />And be careful about LED swapping, too.  A long time ago, I swapped the regular red LED in the NES with a green one.  It was connected the right way round, but still fried something in my NES.  <img src="http://forums.nesdev.com/images/smilies/icon_sad.gif" alt=":-(" title="Sad" /><p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=355">ccovell</a> — Tue May 01, 2007 6:47 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
